01:12:07.580 --> 01:12:10.940
So Thailand, for
example, as you saw,

01:12:10.940 --> 01:12:15.320
had financial deepening
going on, and at times,

01:12:15.320 --> 01:12:18.890
rather substantial
financial deepening.

01:12:18.890 --> 01:12:22.670
Once we have these models
and we've kind of estimated

01:12:22.670 --> 01:12:24.500
or calibrated the
key parameter, we

01:12:24.500 --> 01:12:26.090
can do these
welfare experiments.

01:12:26.090 --> 01:12:32.270
We can actually say, who
benefited, and for that matter,

01:12:32.270 --> 01:12:37.660
who lost from the expansion
of the financial system?

01:12:37.660 --> 01:12:41.800
The beneficiaries are like
these poor credit constrained

01:12:41.800 --> 01:12:45.580
households that don't have
access to the financial system.

01:12:45.580 --> 01:12:47.920
But over time, as
they exogenously

01:12:47.920 --> 01:12:51.580
are allowed to
enter that system,

01:12:51.580 --> 01:12:55.030
they have huge increases in
their welfare and well-being.

01:12:57.610 --> 01:13:00.070
Why does somebody lose?

01:13:00.070 --> 01:13:05.410
Well, that growth of enterprise
means increased employment.

01:13:05.410 --> 01:13:08.360
It's pressure on wages.

01:13:08.360 --> 01:13:11.050
In the model and in Thailand,
the real wage eventually

01:13:11.050 --> 01:13:13.090
shoots up rather dramatically.

01:13:13.090 --> 01:13:15.550
That increases the
cost of doing business

01:13:15.550 --> 01:13:22.160
and the profits of
entrepreneurs can drop.

01:13:22.160 --> 01:13:26.330
So this is the wonderful part.

01:13:26.330 --> 01:13:29.220
Now, I don't mean to say
this model is wonderful.

01:13:29.220 --> 01:13:31.010
It has a lot of
limitations, which I will

01:13:31.010 --> 01:13:32.870
share with you on Thursday.

01:13:32.870 --> 01:13:35.990
But what's wonderful about
it is that you can actually

01:13:35.990 --> 01:13:40.490
go through these distributive
welfare gains and losses

01:13:40.490 --> 01:13:43.250
types of calculations.

01:13:43.250 --> 01:13:48.210
This one with endogenous
financial deepening

01:13:48.210 --> 01:13:50.610
comes back to my comment
on the slide which

01:13:50.610 --> 01:13:54.570
had India versus Thailand,
and I said something obscure

01:13:54.570 --> 01:13:58.320
about I had another view of
what happened in Thailand.

01:13:58.320 --> 01:14:04.110
Well, part of that growth
was preceded by a real flat.

01:14:04.110 --> 01:14:07.560
GDP went basically flat-lined.

01:14:07.560 --> 01:14:08.700
And what was going on?

01:14:08.700 --> 01:14:14.820
Well, they had certain interest
rate restrictions on deposit

01:14:14.820 --> 01:14:16.740
rates and lending rates.

01:14:16.740 --> 01:14:19.250
There was an oil shock.

01:14:19.250 --> 01:14:23.170
Prices were going up,
and money was flowing out

01:14:23.170 --> 01:14:25.920
of the financial system.

01:14:25.920 --> 01:14:28.080
The banks ran into trouble.

01:14:28.080 --> 01:14:30.840
The government essentially
took them over,

01:14:30.840 --> 01:14:34.450
and the economy goes flat-line.

01:14:34.450 --> 01:14:36.770
You should worry about this.

01:14:36.770 --> 01:14:40.720
It's not necessarily the
case that quote, regulation,

01:14:40.720 --> 01:14:45.250
or in this case,
national-- almost close

01:14:45.250 --> 01:14:47.200
to nationalization
of the banking system

01:14:47.200 --> 01:14:52.550
is necessarily the way to deal
with the financial crisis.

01:14:52.550 --> 01:14:54.430
Now how on earth are
we able to model this?

01:14:54.430 --> 01:14:56.330
It's really quite simple.

01:14:56.330 --> 01:14:59.680
We just create a wedge
in the original Greenwood

01:14:59.680 --> 01:15:02.585
and Jovanovic model,
which is the spread

01:15:02.585 --> 01:15:04.210
between the borrowing
and lending rate.

01:15:04.210 --> 01:15:06.160
And we say when the more the--

01:15:06.160 --> 01:15:09.340
sorry, this sounds
very market-oriented--

01:15:09.340 --> 01:15:13.210
the more the government
does, the more resources

01:15:13.210 --> 01:15:17.500
gets squandered, and
that inefficiency wedge

01:15:17.500 --> 01:15:20.920
kind of increases over and above
the cost of intermediation.

01:15:20.920 --> 01:15:22.570
And at the calibrated
parameters,

01:15:22.570 --> 01:15:27.190
that's actually enough for the
model simulation to go flat.

01:15:27.190 --> 01:15:29.860
But likewise, then we can
liberalize the system, which

01:15:29.860 --> 01:15:32.140
Thailand did, and back out.

